notesStmt.note: This illustrated copy of The lamentations of Jeremiah with the gloss (or interpretation) of Gilbert of Auxerre was written in Austria in the second half of the twelfth century and comes from the monastery of Seitenstetten. Gilbert died in 1134, and the manuscript is an early and important witness to his text. The gloss is written in a small script and is both interlinear and marginal. This layout is typical of glossed books of the Bible from the twelfth century. The illustrations of the sack of Jerusalem and the return to Babylon give valuable information on twelfth-century armor. The manuscript is in its original binding.

msContents.textLang: The primary language in this manuscript is Latin.

layoutDesc.layout: Number of actual written lines varies by folio, but main text laid out in 12 lines, with gloss having 48 lines

handDesc.handNote: Written in a late cursive script; both prayers apparently written in the same fifteenth- or sixteenth-century hand

Written in late Caroline minuscule script with very few signs of incoming Gothic features; names of Hebrew letters as section headings in a majuscule display script; added prayers in a different hand on fol. 1r-v

decoDesc.decoNote: Two full-page miniatures; one half-page miniature; two historiated initials, two inhabited initials, and one large decorated initial (all 3 to 4 lines high based on large text line spacing); some chapter prefaces framed by inhabited columns and arcades; all decoration drawn in red, black, and green ink; small red initials throughout (1 to 2 lines high); rubrics in red; text in black ink

binding.p: Plain alum-tawed leather over oak(?) boards; center fore-edge strap meant to fasten to pin on upper board missing; sewn on three alum-tawed straps; endbands of a single rolled alum-tawed core, worked with similar thread to main sewing; double blind lines on each band; saltire cross formed from two double lines on upper board; five small steel studs once on each board, with a six-petaled impression remaining from each of them
